                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d123">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/6–2750: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in India</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-06-27T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 27, 1950—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>642. Madame Pandit was read copy Pres statement re Korea at 11:30 AM, June 27 at
                        <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>. She appeared not too seriously
                    concerned thereby; agreed India had been involved Korean question from
                    beginning; and thought India wld undoubtedly welcome US support of UNSC.</p>
                <p>Although <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> not sanguine Indian reaction will
                    be universally favorable Pres declaration Madame Pandit’s remarks indicate it
                    may be possible vitiate potential original criticism, even win support, by
                    emphasis UN aspects US action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
